{
  "doc_id": "28799",
  "text": "Chronic rhinosinusitis (CRS) is a highly prevalent inflammation of the nose and the paranasal cavities. CRS can be subdivided in CRS without nasal polyps (CRSsNP) and CRS with nasal polyps (CRSwNP) based on clinical parameters, different cytokine pattern and distinct cellular profiles [CITATION_1] . Current data on cytokines expression within sinonasal homogenates [CITATION_2] suggest that maintenance of mucosal health and/or inflammation is not dependent of one T helper cell subset but rather the contribution of several subsets expressed at the same time. Recently different studies demonstrating the presence of IL-5, IL-17 and IFNc, eosinophilic cationic protein (ECP), myeloperoxidase (MPO) and local IgE in homogenatesfrom CRSwNP tissue support the presence of different T cell subsets and consecutive variations in the inflammatory patterns [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . In CRSsNP however, no IL-5 could be detected on protein level by multiplex analysis, but only IFNc protein could be observed, pointing to Th1 cells as orchestrators.",
